<DOC><DOCNO> AP891122-0070 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 0952EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Czechoslovakia-Trial     11-22 0303</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia-Trial,0313</SECOND><HEAD>200 Call for Freedom as Bratislava Trial of Activist Starts</HEAD><HEAD>With PM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD><BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>BRATISLAVA, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   About 200 people prayed andcalled for freedom outside the Palace of Justice today in a protesturging the release of a prominent dissident on trial for seditionand subversion.   Jan Carnogursky, a Roman Catholic activist and human rightscampaigner, went on trial Monday on charges filed on the basis ofone article written for a Bratislava underground monthly and astatement signed with four other activists in August.   If convicted, he faces up to 10 years in jail.   The four other activists were detained with Carnogursky on Aug.14, but they were tried Nov. 14 and allowed to remain free pendingtheir trial.   One of them, Miroslav Kusy, a leading Slovak rights activist,was given an eight-month suspended sentence after being convictedof ``harming state interests abroad.''   The three other activists, Hana Ponicka, Anton Selecky andVladimir Manak, who were charged with sedition together withCarnogursky, were acquitted.   Carnogursky's trial began Nov. 6 but was immediately adjournedbecause his defense lawyer became ill.   About 200 people gathered outside the Palace of Justice as thetrial was under way today, praying and singing religious songs.Several people held up tiny crosses.   As a speaker called for the release of Carnogurksy, the crowdburst into chants of ``Freedom! Freedom!''   Police blocked off the immediate area to traffic, but they didnot intervene in the protest.   The small demonstration broke up broke up after two hours.Police were standing at the door of the Palace of Justice andseveral were posted in nearby street, including a few directly infront of the demonstrators.   In front of the demonstrators, a Czechoslovak flag andphotographs were pinned to a lamppost.</TEXT></DOC>